{{Infobox protected area | name = Santuario de Fauna y Flora El Corchal "El mono Hernández" | alt_name = "El mono Hernández" Cork Forest Flora and Fauna Sanctuary | iucn_category = III | photo = | photo_alt = | photo_caption = | photo_width = | map = Colombia |relief = 1 | map_alt = | map_caption = | map_width = | location = | nearest_city = | coords = {{coord|10|3|0|N|75|20|0|W|display=inline, title}} | coords_ref = | region = | area = {{convert|38.5|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} | established = 5 August 2002 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = [[National System of Protected Areas (Colombia)|SINAP]] | world_heritage_site = | url = }}
The '''"El mono Hernández" Cork Forest Flora and Fauna Sanctuary''' ({{lang-es|Santuario de Fauna y Flora El Corchal "El mono Hernández"}}) is a [[natural monument]] located in the [[Sucre Department|Sucre]] and [[Bolívar Department]]s on the coast of the [[Caribbean Region of Colombia]].
The park is named in honor of Colombian naturalist Jorge Ignacio "El Mono" Hernández-Camacho (1935–2001), one of the founders of Colombia's [[National Natural Parks System (Colombia)|National Natural Park System]].<ref name="Villegas109">{{harvnb|Villegas|Sesana|2007| p=109}}</ref>
==Climate== Average temperature is 28°C and yearly rainfall is 1100&nbsp;mm with the largest precipitation in April and November. The warmest months are June and July, and the driest period is between December and April.<ref name="Villegas110">{{harvnb|Villegas|Sesana|2007| p=110}}</ref>
==Flora and fauna== [[Mangrove]] and cork swamp forests are protected within the area. Mangroves covers about half of the area, located in the western and northern parts of the sanctuary.<ref name="Villegas110" /><ref name="Parque Nacional">{{cite web | url = http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=01.0142 | title = Santuario de Flora y Fauna El Corchal "El Mono Hernández" | publisher = Parques Nacionales Naturales de Colombia | accessdate = 10 July 2010 | language = Spanish }}</ref> The mangroves are dominated by five species, [[Rhizophora mangle|red mangrove]], [[avicennia germinans|black mangrove]], [[Laguncularia racemosa|white mangrove]], [[Conocarpus erectus|buttonwood]] and neotropical mangrove.<ref name="Villegas110" /> The swamps is the only place in the [[Caribbean Region of Colombia|Colombian Caribbean Region]] where pure ''corchales'', "[[Cork (material)|cork]]" forests, grow, dominated by ''[[Pterocarpus]] officinalis'', and with a total area of 401 hectares.<ref name="Parque Nacional" />
It is home to 153 species of birds,<ref name="Ciencia">{{cite web |url=http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=01.014203 |title=Naturaleza y Ciencia del Santuario de Flora y Fauna El Corchal "El Mono Hernández" |publisher=Parques Nacionales Naturales de Colombia |accessdate=10 July 2010 |language=Spanish |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722114452/http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=01.014203 |archivedate=22 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> the great diversity is due to the quantity of food produced in the surrounding waters.<ref name="Villegas110" /> A number of species feed on the marsh vegetation, including the endangered [[West Indian manatee]]. Other noteworthy animals are the [[jaguar]], [[brown caiman]]<ref name="Villegas110" /> and [[howler monkey]].<ref name="Woods53">{{harvnb|Woods|2008| p=53}}</ref>
