{{Infobox zoo |zoo_name = L'Oceanogràfic |logo = |logo_caption = |image = L'Oceanografic, Valencia, Spain 2 - Jan 07-cropped.jpg |image_caption = Entrance to the marine complex |location = [[Valencia, Spain]] |date_opened = 14 February 2003 |date_closed = |coordinates = {{Coord|39.45279|-0.34812|display=it|scale:10000}} |area = {{Convert|110000|m2}}<ref name=size>L'Oceanogràfic: ''[http://www.cac.es/oceanografic/know/ Know.]'' Retrieved 24 December 2013</ref> |num_species = 500 |num_animals = 45,000 |largest_tank_vol = |total_tank_vol = {{Convert|42000000|l|gal}}<ref name=size/> |annual_visitors = |members = |exhibits = |website = {{URL|https://www.oceanografic.org/}} }}
'''L'Oceanogràfic''' ({{IPA-ca|loseˌanoˈɣɾafik|langva}}; {{lang-es|El Oceanográfico}} {{IPA-es|el oˌθe.anoˈɣɾafiko|}}, "The Oceanographic") is an [[oceanarium]] situated in the east of the city of [[Valencia, Spain]], where different marine habitats are represented. It was designed by the architect [[Félix Candela]] and the structural engineers [[Alberto Domingo]] and [[Carlos Lázaro]]. It is integrated inside the cultural complex known as the [[City of Arts and Sciences|Ciutat de les Arts i de les Ciències]] (City of Arts and Sciences). It was opened on 14 February 2003.
==General information== [[File:L'Oceanografic (Valencia, Spain) 01.jpg|thumb|left|The underwater restaurant]]
{{multiple image <!-- Essential parameters --> | align = left | direction = horizontal <!-- Images --> | total_width = 480 <!--image 1--> | image1 = White Shark Valencia's oceanografic.jpg | width1 = 443 | height1 = 278 | caption1 = [[Sand tiger shark|Sand tiger sharks]] in the ocean tank <!--image 2--> | image2 = L'Oceanografic, Valencia, Spain 3 - Jan 07.jpg | width2 = 4032 | height2 = 2687 | caption2 = Mediterranean [[seagrass]] aquarium <!--image 3--> | image3 = Beluga oceanografic.jpg | width3 = 3072 | height3 = 2304 | caption3 = A [[beluga whale|beluga]] in the arctic tank }}
The Oceanographic is the largest complex of its type in Europe , with a surface of {{Convert|110000|m2}} and a water capacity of {{Convert|42000000|l|gal}}.<ref name=size/> This includes a {{Convert|26000000|l|gal|adj=on}} [[dolphinarium]] and a {{Convert|7000000|l|gal|adj=on}} ocean tank with [[shark]]s, [[Batoidea|rays]] and other fish.<ref name=size/> There are 45,000 animals of 500 different species including fish, mammals, birds, reptiles and invertebrates — amongst these are sharks, [[penguin]]s, [[dolphin]]s, [[sea lion]]s, [[walrus]]es, [[Beluga (whale)|beluga]] whales, and more — all inhabiting nine underwater towers. Each tower is structured in two levels and represent the major ecosystems of the planet.
The park is divided into ten areas. The marine areas reflect the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] habitats, the polar oceans — the [[Arctic]], the islands, the tropical seas, the temperate seas and the [[Red Sea]]. The park also includes a dolphinarium, an auditorium with a Red Sea aquarium, an area of [[mangrove swamp]]s and [[marshland]], and a garden with more than 80 different species of plant.
The sea water is pumped from the beach of ''La Malva-Rosa'' having passed all of the necessary requirements for quality.
The architecture of the complex is a work of the architect [[Félix Candela]] and the engineers [[Alberto Domingo]] and [[Carlos Lázaro]], who made the structural design of the concrete coverings of the buildings.
==Transportation== L'Oceanogràfic can be reached via Metro, disembark at Alameda Station or through bus number 15 and 95.
